        <LEXMeaning Id="003489001003000" IsBiblicalTerm="M" EntryCode="3.4" Indent="0">
          <LEXDomains>
            <LEXDomain>Plants</LEXDomain>
          </LEXDomains>
          <LEXSubDomains>
            <LEXSubDomain>Trees</LEXSubDomain>
          </LEXSubDomains>
          <LEXSenses>
            <LEXSense LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="2021-12-11 13:05:53" LastEditedBy="">
              <DefinitionLong/>
              <DefinitionShort>large perennial plant, usually having a woody central stem, called a trunk, with secondary branches growing from it.</DefinitionShort>
              <Glosses>
                <Gloss>tree</Gloss>
              </Glosses>
              <Comments>It is also possible to understand ξύλον in {S:04202303100012} as ‘firewood.’ One may therefore translate the first part of this conditional sentence as ‘if they do these things to firewood which has recently been cut’ or ‘if they do these things to firewood which hasn’t dried out’ (see {D:3.61}).|In {S:06600200700036} and {S:06602200200024} ξύλον τῆς ζωῆς ‘tree of life’ may cause certain complications if the passage is translated more or less literally ‘I will give him to eat of the tree of life.’ In some languages a literal rendering would mean ‘to gnaw on the tree of life,’ that is to say, to eat the wood or the bark. It may therefore be necessary to translate ‘to eat the fruit of the tree of life’ or ‘… the fruit from the tree that causes life’ or ‘… causes people to live.’</Comments>
            </LEXSense>
          </LEXSenses>
